# Project: Production FastAPI backend + OpenAI Responses API

## Test Gate Policy (strict)

1) BEFORE changes: run the existing test suite (pytest). If failing, warn and stop.
2) AFTER changes: run full test suite. Task is not complete unless all tests pass
   (except when explicitly writing a failing test in TDD).

## Documentation Gate (mandatory)

Update any impacted docs proportionally (README.md, API.md, RISKS-AND-IMPROVEMENTS.md,
docstrings, env vars in settings). Prefer updating existing docs.

## Stack & practices

- FastAPI with APIRouter + Depends.
- Pydantic v2 / pydantic-settings (settings.py).
- Official OpenAI Python client.
- Async-first: if the app is async, do not introduce sync I/O in request path.
- pytest (+ pytest-asyncio if async).
- Respect existing tooling (ruff/black/mypy if present).

## Architecture (Hexagonal / Clean) – MUST MATCH CURRENT FOLDERS

Use the existing structure. Do NOT invent new top-level folders.

- app/api = entrypoints (routes, middleware, schemas). Keep routers thin.
- app/application = use cases + ports (interfaces). No framework or infra imports.
- app/domain = domain logic (pure Python). No imports from api/application/infra.
- app/infra = adapters / infrastructure (OpenAI + persistence + logging). External libs allowed.

Dependency direction (strict):
api -> application -> domain
infra -> application/domain (implements ports)

Forbidden:
- domain importing from application/api/infra
- application importing from api/infra/openai/sqlalchemy

## OpenAI integration rules (mandatory)

- OPENAI_API_KEY from environment only.
- Always set timeouts.
- Handle transient errors + rate limits with basic retry/backoff if needed.
- Never log full prompts or sensitive user data. Apply data minimization.
- Use consistent response envelope patterns.

## Observability

Logs must include request_id, endpoint, status_code, latency.
Prefer centralized error handling, avoid scattered try/except.

## Transactions & persistence

- SQLAlchemy repo in app/infra/persistence must NOT call commit().
- commit/rollback must be managed at a higher level (Unit of Work or request scope).
- Repos should do add/flush and return ids/data.

Before coding:
- State which layers/files you will touch.
- Confirm you will not introduce forbidden imports.